The salt and lime juice are not listed but dont forget them. They make a difference. This is a permenant part of my summer menu.

Rating: 4
Delicious! This recipe is so easy and foolproof--I served this at a party alongside a salad and vegetarian tacos and everyone loved it (in fact the cilantro-lime mayo was great on the tacos as well). I used both regular baking potatoes & sweet potatoes, and it was a nice mix. I also discovered at the last minute that I was out of cumin so I just used some taco seasoning that I had on hand and it worked out great (though I would still like to try the recipe as written). I think this is one of those recipes that's pretty difficult to mess up!

Rating: 4
This was quick and easy. My husband definitely enjoyed them. Don't skip the mayo...it is delicious!

Rating: 3
This was easy, and tasty though I kept them in the oven too long so be careful. This is a great side that can accompany many entrees. I used only 2 med-large baking potatoes, and included 1/2 tsp. salt with the cumin and oregano and 2 tblsp olive oil. I squeezed half a lime into the mayo in addition to the zest. I would try a quarter of lime the next time and more cilanto.

Rating: 4
Yum. Not a huge potato fan, but the fries were delish, and the sauce is wonderful on everything. I do add a good squeeze of lime juice to it as well (the directions seemed a little iff-y on that), but I think it makes a big difference. It's great on fish tacos, too!

Rating: 4
Gosh darn this is fabulous! The lime in the dip makes this seem so light and refreshing. Mine cooked to a rich crunch in only 20 minutes. For half of them I used a seasoning (like Old Bay) and they are equally as yummy. I also dusted them before the oven with some smoked paprika. I'll go back to this recipe again!

